The Synthetic Causal Framework

An NLP-based Solution to the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference

Emil Meyer-Hansen1

Version: 2024-10-16-15-16

1 Abstract

When testing theorized causal relationships, a Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT) is broadly considered the scientific golden standard for inferring causation, but this method requires the theorized cause to be manipulable. Researchers interested in a non-manipulable theorized cause are therefore unable to reliably draw causal inference. This recognized shortcoming has previously been addressed by methodologists, who have developed numerous alternatives that enable such researchers to draw causal inference. However, these methods often require untestable and dubious assumptions, and their applicability similarly varies. This can defeat their intended goal of providing reliable causal inference. This paper addresses these shortcomings by introducing a novel alternative: The Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF), which is widely applicable across disciplines and guarantees the high internal validity necessary for reliable causal inference. Formalized using the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (Imbens and Rubin 2015), the SCF offers a synthetic solution to the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference (Holland 1986) by estimating causal effects through intra-unit comparisons of counterfactual outcomes, enabling unbiased comparisons across any level of manipulation. This involves synthesizing simulated data and real-world data using Natural Language Processing (NLP) models, producing synthetic units, where each unit can be simultaneously exposed to all levels of manipulation. Causal inference can then be reliably drawn using standard statistical models. A proof-of-concept of the SCF is provided, in the form of a small-scale Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT), which implements OpenAIs GPT-4o-mini and Bayesian mixed effects models to successfully replicate the established relationship between social deservingness and welfare support (Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019). By replicating a robust human-based result solely using synthetic respondents, this provides evidence that SCF-based results can be generalized to human populations. Practical implications of the SCF are discussed, which includes the ability of researchers to generally and reliably draw causal inference when the theorized cause would normally be non-manipulable. A limitation of the SCF is the reliance on NLP-models that restricts its implementation to text-based environments. Other advantages include substantially reduced financial and time costs compared to human studies. While the generalizability of SCF-based results to human populations should remain a relevant concern, advances in the NLP-models are likely to reduce such concern and further increase the advantages of adopting the SCF for applied research.

Keywords: Synthetic Causal Framework, SCF, Synthetically Controlled Trial, SCT, Causal inference, Causal framework, Causal methodology, Causal design, Experimental design, Potential Outcomes Framework, Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference, Natural Language Processing, NLP, Generative Pretrained Transformer, GPT, Political methodology, Political science, Social deservingness, Welfare support, Welfare attitudes, Evolutionary psychology, Conceptual replication

4 Methodology

To justify the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF) empirically, as well as help researchers implement it, a proof-of-concept is provided in the form of a demonstration. This will specifically involve a small-scale replication of the established relationship between social deservingness and welfare support. The effect of social deservingness has been identified as positive, statistically discernible from zero (\(p .05\)), and practically significant (\(r .3\), Funder and Ozer 2019) across multiple US-based studies (Aare and Petersen 2014; Kane et al. 2023; Mummolo and Peterson 2019), which employ survey experiments (Gaines et al. 2006) to achieve reliable causal inference. A meta-analysis (Eysenck 1995; Glass 1976; Sharpe and Poets 2020) is conducted on these studies using a Bayesian mixed-effects model (e.g., Maier et al. 2022), producing an estimated weighted average effect of .32 (SD = .07; 95% HDI[.16; .48]), which will be the exact effect to replicate. The following sections cover (1) the procedure for simulating data in a manner that makes respondent characteristics more representative of the US population; (2) how to use OpenAIs API to call the gpt-4o-mini NLP-model (OpenAI 2024a) to transform the simulated respondents into synthetic respondents by generating life-histories, making their behavior less artificial and more human; (3) implementing a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) and parallel worlds-estimation to unbiasedly measure each synthetic respondents counterfactual support for tightening welfare requirements when exposed to vignettes describing a lazy or unlucky welfare recipient; and (4) using statistical inference to estimate the causal effect of social (un)deservingness on welfare support. Following recommendations for reproducible and transparent research (e.g., Alister et al. 2021; Lenz and Sahn 2021; Open Science Collaboration 2015; Peng 2011; Ritchie 2021), this project subscribes to the open science standard (Christensen et al. 2019; Nosek et al. 2012, 2015), with this demonstration of the SCF being done with the free and open-source R programming language (R Core Team 2024) and RStudio IDE (Posit Team 2024), which is especially suited for data science (Welbers et al. 2017: 245) and reproducible research (Krotov and Tennyson 2018: 171). Accordingly, code for implementing this demonstration is provided as R syntax in the markdown (Gruber 2014) version of this file (not made available in this preview version), and software specifications, used R packages, and descriptive statistics of the data are provided in the appendix.

4.1 Simulating Data

As previously mentioned, simulating data allows the researcher to decide which characteristics the NLP-model should base its life-history and responses on. While OpenAIs gpt-4o-mini is expectedly capable of inferring characteristics proportional to a population by basing them on their prevalence in its training data (OpenAI 2024a), explicitly determining the characteristics gives the researcher more control over the characteristics generated, which could impact the behavior of the synthetic respondents and how generalizable results are to the population of interest. While it can be expected that the greater the number of simulated characteristics, the more realistic the behavior of the NLP, in terms of specifically which and how many characteristics to simulate, answers to these questions will likely vary depending on characteristics found relevant for the particular research topic. For this demonstration, the common demographics (e.g., ANES 2021; Ruggles et al. 2024) of US State residence, area residence, number of children in household, sex, age, marital status, ethnoracial group2, highest level of education, employment status, and household income ($US) will be simulated, which will likely provide gpt-4o-mini with plenty of information to base its life-histories on. Furthermore, since the results from Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023) relate specifically to political attitudes to welfare requirements, the characteristics of political party affiliation and political ideology will also be simulated.

Simulating characteristics can be done so that their prevalence in the data is proportional to a national population of interest. Since this demonstration focuses on the US-based results from Aare and Petersen (2014), and its replications by Mummolo and Peterson (2019) and Kane et al. (2023), the national population of interest is the adult population of the United States of America (US). A population-proportional simulation of characteristics can be achieved by constructing a stratification matrix using large samples such as those that form the basis of census data. A stratification matrix consists of every combination of the characteristics of interest and their frequency in the population, and a US-based version can be constructed using US Census Bureau data provided by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024). Here, the 2022-wave is especially useful for this project due to containing contemporary measures of most characteristics to simulate and a large sample size (n) of 3,373,378 respondents. However, the data lacks measures of political party affiliation and political ideology, meaning that these measures will have to be imputed (Kalton and Kasprzyk 1982; King et al. 2001; Rubin 1988).

To impute the measures of political party affiliation and political ideology, data from the similarly recent 2020-wave of the American National Election Survey (ANES 2021) can be used. While the ANES relies on samples substantially smaller than the IPUMS (n = 8,280), it contains similar measures of all characteristics to simulate. This can be used to train statistical models to impute political party and ideology by recoding all variables to have the same categories and scale across the IPUMS and ANES. Following the methodology of cross-validation (Stone 1974), an unbiased measure of the imputation accuracy of statistical models can be derived by splitting the ANES data into a train and test dataset, using the conventional 80/20 split ratio (e.g., Frana et al. 2024), training the models on the training data and testing their imputation accuracy on the testing data. To assess variability in imputation accuracy, Bootstrapped (or Monte-Carlo) cross-validation (Xu and Liang 2001) is used, which involves iteratively splitting and testing models a total of 10 times. To impute the dichotomously-coded preferred political party of respondents, a Hierarchical Bernoulli (Gelman and Hill 2007) and a Random Forest (Breiman 2001; Ho 1995; Liaw and Wiener 2002) model are compared. From their predictions, a confusion matrix (Tharwat 2018) is generated, with imputation accuracy being computed as the arithmetic mean of the total accuracy (ACC), sensitivity (i.e., recall) and specificity (Yerushalmy 1947), positive predictive value (PPV; i.e., precision) and negative predictive value (NPV) (Altman and Bland 1994), which are popular, complementary metrics of model accuracy. The imputation accuracy of the Hierarchical Bernoulli is .66, with a standard deviation (SD) of .01, while the Random Forest model has an imputation accuracy of .65 (SD = .01), meaning that the Hierarchical Bernoulli is chosen to impute political party in the IPUMS data due to its (marginally) superior accuracy. Imputing political ideology, which could be treated either as an ordered or (less appropriately) as a continuous variable, involves a Hierarchical Gaussian model (Gelman and Hill 2007), a Generalized Additive Model (GAM, Hastie and Tibshirani 1990; Wood 2004, 2011, 2017), and a Random Forest model. These are similarly evaluated, though given its non-dichotomous coding, only ACC is used to measure imputation accuracy. These models produce an ACC of .30 (.01), .30 (.01), and .43 (.01), respectively, resulting in the Random Forest model being chosen to impute political ideology for its superior accuracy.

Having imputed preferred political party and political idelogy in the IPUMS data, all chosen characteristics are available, and a stratification matrix is generated by counting the frequency of every combination of the characteristics. Then, analogous to a non-parametric bootstrap (Efron 1979, 2003), simulating data can done by sampling with replacement from the stratification matrix, with the sampling probability being the frequency of each combination of characteristics. This ensures that the value of each characteristic is simulated conditionally on the values of all the other characteristics (e.g., P(sex = Male | State = Tennessee, Age = 65, Political Ideology = Conservative)), making the resulting data reflect the proportionality of characteristics in the US population. Asymptotically, data simulated in this manner is representative of the national population of interest, and for smaller datasets that nonetheless are unrepresentative, the multilevel regression and poststratification (MRP, Gelman and Little 1997) method can be used to adjust for such sample-population imbalances. With this US-based stratification matrix available, a sample can then easily be generated. For the purposes of this brief demonstration, a small sample of 100 simulated respondents is generated, which, given that two counterfactual outcomes are observed for each respondent, provides an effective sample size of 200. With regard to succesfully replicating the aforementioned effect size of .32 with an \(\alpha\) level of .05 and 2 model parameters (i.e., intercept and coefficient, see model below), the statistical power (Gelman and Carlin 2014) is 99.52%, which can be considered adequate (Cohen 1988, 1991). Similarly, the type M error rate (Gelman and Carlin 2014) is 1.00, meaning that the effect is unlikely to be under-/overestimated, while the type S error rate (Gelman and Carlin 2014) is .00%, indicating almost no probability of the estimate having the wrong sign. As such, the probability of a successful replication is high, at least as indicated by these metrics.

This produces a 100 \(\times\) 13 dataframe, with examples of observations in the dataframe being provided in table 4.1. The data contains an identification number (id) and the 12 measures of the selected characteristics of each simulated respondent: Their US state of residence (e.g., Missouri, Connecticut, Ohio), number of children (range: 0 - 3), sex (i.e., Female, Male), age (range: 18 - 86), marital status (e.g., Married, Not Married, Divorced), ethnoracial group (e.g., Puerto Rican, Filipino, Peruvian), level of education (range: Less Than High School Credential - Graduate Degree), employment status (e.g., Not In Labor Force, Unemployed, Employed), household income (range: 0 - 378,500; median: 77,750, $US), preferred political party (i.e., Republican Party, Democratic Party), and political ideology (range: Extremely Liberal - Extremely Conservative). For an overview, descriptive statistics are provided both metrically and graphically in the appendix.

While the sample, on average, manages to capture 91.74% (SD = 15.27pp) of the information in the US population3, an inspection of the distributions reveals some persisting differences, especially in preferred political party and ideology, where there is an overrepresentation of republicans and conservatives relative to the US population. Contrary to what was previously implied by the type M metric, this sample-population imbalance could cause an overestimated effect size, since the effect of social deservingness could interact with republicanism/conservatism, as democrats/liberals are expectedly more favorable of welfare support than republicans/conservatives, meaning that social deservingness likely matters more for the welfare support of conservatives than liberals. As such, the estimated average effect will likely be overestimated due to the overrepresentation of republican/conservative synthetic respondents, for whom the effect is expectedly larger. Nonetheless, these unrepresentative characteristics can be attributed not to sampling bias but to chance due to the relatively small sample size. Future studies can address such sample-population imbalances by generating larger samples with the stratification matrix to make data more representative. With this simulated data now having been generated, OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini can then be used to generate their life-histories.

4.2 Generating Life-Histories

With simulated data available, input can be engineered to prompt the NLP-model to generate life-histories for the respondents. A life-history (Rosenthal 2018) can be considered a narrative by which individuals (chronologically) frame their life, experiences, identity, relationships, existential purpose and place in society (e.g., Znaniecki and Thomas 2020[1974]). As previously mentioned, the purpose of life-histories is to provide more character and nuance to the simulated respondents in a way that goes beyond their assigned characteristics. This will expectedly help the NLP-model respond in a manner that is consistent with a human possessing the assigned characteristics, as human behavior is arguably more nuanced and complicated than what can be characterized by a relatively few set of characteristics. Prompting the NLP-model to generate the life-history based on their assigned characteristics helps ensure that other characteristics generated in the life-history are functions of the explicitly determined characteristics. An example of a contemporaneous iteration of a prompt useful for generating life-histories is provided in table 4.2.

Table 4.2: How To Generate A Life-History
id Prompt
19

You are to act as a character and must remain in character for the purposes of a roleplay scenario. You and your thus refer to your character from now on. Your character has the following characteristics:

Country: United States of America (USA)

State: Arkansas

Urban: Small Town Or Surburb

Number of Children in Household: 0

Sex: Female

Age: 53

Marital Status: Married

Ethonoracial Group: Mexican

Household Income ($US): 30000

Education: High School Credential

Employment Status: Not In Labor Force

Preferred Political Party: Democratic Party

Political Ideology: Moderate; Middle Of The Road

Be creative but realistic and compose a brief life-history for your character based on the provided characteristics:

NOTE: The prompt was generated through trial-and-error and should be considered a non-authoritative and possibly suboptimal example of how to generate life-histories for simulated respondents using NLP-models. The characteristics in the prompt are based on data by the IPUMS (Ruggles et al. 2024) and ANES (2021).

The prompt aims to specify that the NLP-model is to act as a character and to persistently remain in character. This serves to ensure that all output generated by the NLP reflects behavior consistent with that character. It also contains a list of all the assigned characteristics, followed by a request for it to generate a (brief) life-history based on these characteristics. Increasing the number of provided characteristics and length of the generated life-history likely results in behavior that more realistically reflects a human possessing these traits, though at greater financial costs and time needed by the NLP-model to process the input and generate an output. The models max length (i.e., max_tokens) parameter can be restricted to reduce costs (OpenAI 2024b), though this will likely reduce its ability to act in a manner consistent with its assigned characteristics. The optimal max length likely varies across different research purposes, and for this demonstration the max_tokens for generating life-histories is set to 500, which is found to be adequate within this context. Another OpenAI parameter is the temperature (or randomness) of the NLP-models output. A higher value makes its output adhere less to language syntax, making its output less cohesive and meaningful. The default value by OpenAI is 1, and while an optimal value will likely vary across contexts, this value is similarly found to be adequate for the context of generating life-histories in this demonstration.

To generate life-histories from the simulated data, it is recommended to use OpenAIs API. Requests processed through their API are not used to train their models and is deleted after 30 days (OpenAI 2024c), thus reducing concerns about privacy and whether prompt engineering inadvertently trains the model, resulting in findings that reflect researcher preferences rather than human behavior, possibly resulting in tautological results. Compared to manually generating life-histories, calling the API using software exponentially speeds up the process and is easily done through R in RStudio. To this end, this demonstration relies on the openai R package (Rudnytskyi 2023). Due to the speed of such software, it is furthermore recommended to enforce pauses between calls to the API to reduce traffic, which can stress their systems. OpenAI already enforces rate limits, and to avoid unintentionally hitting one of their numerous request limitations (OpenAI 2024b), the researcher can a priori enforce a pause between requests. This demonstration uses a pause of 3.1 seconds, though values could vary depending on the number and length of requests.

This demonstration implements and recommends that NLP-output is generated separately for each simulated respondent. An alternative to this is batching, which involves grouping multiple requests together into a single request (OpenAI 2024b). For example, by providing the characteristics of several simulated respondents in the same prompt and asking for multiple life-histories. While this can reduce both financial and time costs, a serious methodological concern of batching is that generating life-histories (and most other types of outcome) in batches produces output that is interdependent, which typically is not desirable. For example, output generated in batches may be more strongly correlated than output generated in other batches or output generated individually. This would violate the common statistical assumption of observations being identically and independently distributed (iid, Gaenssler and Stute 1979), which will likely need to be adjusted for using statistical modeling (e.g., hierarchical models, Gelman and Hill 2007). Furthermore, when generating the outcome across different group conditions using batching, there may be information spill-over, for example, if the NLP-model mistakes a manipulated with a non-manipulated unit or if the mere presence of information relating to both group conditions affects the generation of results. This spill-over would violate the assumption of stable unit treatment value assumption (SUTVA, Cox 1958; Gelman et al. 2021: 353-354; Rosenbaum and Rubin 1983; Rubin 1974), which is fundamental to causal inference (Angrist et al. 1996; Imbens and Rubin 2015: 9-12). While methods could be implemented to account for this information spill-over (Imbens and Rubin 2015: 12-13; e.g., Aronow and Samii 2017), these can be complex (Rosenbaum 2007), and as similarly argued by Elizabeth Stuart (2010: 3), the most effective solution is simply to prevent interdependency and spill-over by design. As such, to prevent violations of iid and SUTVA in this manner, it is recommended to generate life-histories and most other types of outcome separately, unless the purpose specifically is to study interdependency.

With the specifications and considerations in mind, a life-history for each simulated resondent can be generated. In this demonstration, this involves a for-loop, which iteratively goes through each respondent, makes a call to OpenAIs API for the selected gpt-4o-mini NLP-model, and saves the output to the data. The loop accounts for possible errors in calling the API by waiting 10 seconds before trying again. Information about the output generation provided by OpenAI is saved, such as the time of the request, which help provide documentation of the data. The number of tokens used and the time it took to generate the output is also stored, which will be used to ascertain financial and time costs. Note that before it is possible to call OpenAIs API, researchers must create an OpenAI account, deposit finances, and generate a unique API key (OpenAI 2024b). The key will be used to connect your requests with your finances and should thus be kept private. Following this, the below R code for the for-loop can be executed:

# Initialize columns for storing the GPT-output
simulated_data$life_history_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_id_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_object_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_created_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_model_gpt <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_prompt_tokens <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_completion_tokens <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_logprobs <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_finish_reason <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_message.refusal <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_message.role <- NA
simulated_data$life_history_time_cost <- NA


# Construct prompt
messages_life_history <- list()
messages_life_history[[1]] <- list(
  "role" = "system",
  "content" = "You are a human simulator."
)
messages_life_history[[2]] <- list(
  "role" = "user",
  "content" = NA
)


# A progress bar is useful for keeping track of the progress of the loop
pb <- txtProgressBar(min = 0, max = nrow(simulated_data), style = 3)


# The for-loop
for(i in 1:nrow(simulated_data)){
  
  # Start time recording
  t0 <- Sys.time()

  
  # Enforce a pause if this is the second iteration or higher
  if(i > 1){
    Sys.sleep(pause_duration)
  }
  
  
  # Adjust prompt to reflect respondent i's characteristics
  messages_life_history[[2]][2] <- list(paste0(
    "You are to act as a character and must remain in character for the purposes of a roleplay scenario. 'You' and 'your' thus refer to your character from now on. Your character has the following characteristics:
    Country: United States of America (USA)
    State: ", simulated_data$state[i], "
    Urban: ", simulated_data$urban[i], "
    Number of Children in Household: ", simulated_data$children[i], "
    Sex: ", simulated_data$sex[i], "
    Age: ", simulated_data$age[i], "
    Marriage Status: ", simulated_data$married[i], "
    Race/Ethnicity: ", simulated_data$race_d[i], "
    Household Income: ", simulated_data$household_income_d[i], "
    Education: ", simulated_data$education[i], "
    Employment Status: ", simulated_data$employment[i], "
    Preferred Political Party: ", simulated_data$political_party[i], "
    Political Ideology: ", simulated_data$political_ideology[i], "
    Be creative but realistic and compose a brief life-history for your character based on the provided characteristics:"
  ))

  
  # Call GPT model (and use tryCatch to make the loop continue retrying if encountering an error)
  while(TRUE){
    tryCatch(
      expr = {
        gpt_output <- openai::create_chat_completion(
          model = selected_gpt_model,
          messages = messages_life_history,
          max_tokens = max_tokens$life_history,
          temperature = temperature$life_history,
          openai_api_key = OPENAI_API_KEY
        )
      },
      error = function(e){
        print(paste("Error encountered. Error message:", e))
        print(" Going to sleep for 10 seconds ...")
        Sys.sleep(time = 10)
      }
    )
    break
  }


  # Store life history
  simulated_data$life_history_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$choices$message.content


  # Store utility info
  simulated_data$life_history_id_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$id
  simulated_data$life_history_object_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$object
  simulated_data$life_history_created_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$created
  simulated_data$life_history_model_gpt[i] <- gpt_output$model
  simulated_data$life_history_prompt_tokens[i] <- gpt_output$usage$prompt_tokens
  simulated_data$life_history_completion_tokens[i] <- gpt_output$usage$completion_tokens
  simulated_data$life_history_logprobs[i] <- gpt_output$choices$logprobs
  simulated_data$life_history_finish_reason[i] <- gpt_output$choices$finish_reason
  simulated_data$life_history_message.refusal[i] <- gpt_output$choices$message.refusal
  simulated_data$life_history_message.role[i] <- gpt_output$choices$message.role
  

  # Update progress bar
  setTxtProgressBar(pb, i)
  
  
  # End and store time recording
  t1 <- Sys.time()
  simulated_data$life_history_time_cost <- t1-t0
}


# Convert Unix Timestamp to Datatime
simulated_data$life_history_datetime <- as_datetime(simulated_data$life_history_created_gpt)

Using the aforementioned specifications, generating 100 life-histories using this for-loop takes 15.00 minutes, with the expected time-cost per simulated respondent thus being 9.00 (SD = .00) seconds. Output from the gpt-4o-mini model can be gauged to ascertain whether it ran into any issues during the generation (OpenAI 2024b). This includes its finish_reason, where stop is consistent with no issues, while length means that the life-histories were cut short due to the model reaching the specified max_tokens limitation. Another output parameter is message.refusal, which indicates whether the model refused to provide an output, and this should generally equal NA. A message refusal can happen for several reasons and retries or changing the input may fix the issue. To provide more intuition about a life-history, an example is provided in table 4.3.

It is here recommended to validate that the life-histories reflect and are consistent with the assigned characteristics. This serves to ensure that future output by the model correctly draws on the assigned characteristics. Analogous to qualitative methodology or computational text analysis (Theocharis and Jungherr 2021), validations can be performed by coders, who read the generated life-history and compare it to the assigned characteristics. Coders can provide their evaluations of consistency in numerous formats, for example, dichotomously (e.g., Consistent, Inconsistent), continuously (e.g., 5-point Likert scale), or in open-text format. The number of coders and evaluated life-histories can vary, for example, two independent coders, who evaluate all life-histories or a random sample, with the scope of the evaluation likely depending on the resources available for the given project. Coder evaluations can then be assessed to ascertain their inter-coder reliability (Saal et al. 1980), which expresses whether coders are generally in agreement on the (in)consistency of the output. If coder evaluations are provided in a quantifiable format, this can be estimated as a reliability coefficient, for example, as percent agreement, Sklars \(\omega\) (Hughes 2022), Krippendorffs \(\alpha\) (2018), Fleiss \(\kappa\) (1971), Cohens \(\kappa\) (1960), Scotts \(\pi\) (1955), Spearmans \(\rho\) (1904), Kendalls (1938), or Pearson-Galtons r (Pearson 1895a)4, depending on the number of coders and the scale used to measure (in)consistency. If the same coder has evaluated the same output multiple times, intra-coder reliability (Saal et al. 1980) can also be similarly estimated. An alternative procedure to human coders is to have NLP-models act as coders, which can reduce financial and time costs related to evaluating the consistency of the model output. If doing this, it can be specified that temperature = 0, which increases the determinism of the NLP-coders, expectedly producing a perfect inter- and intra-coder reliability. However, this may under-/overestimate consistency and caution in choosing to use NLP-coders is advised, as it reduces human supervision and quality control over the output.

With life-histories now generated from the simulated characteristics, this synthesis of simulated data and NLP-based data can be considered to have produced synthetic data, which enables a more realistic investigation of the effect of social-deservingness on welfare support. This allows a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) to be conducted, with the purpose being the simultaneous measurement of the counterfactual outcomes for all synthetic respondents.

4.3 Conducting an SCT

With synthetic data having been produced through the synthesis of simulated data and NLP-based data, a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) can then be conducted to generate and measure both potential outcomes of all synthetic respondents, producing an unbiased and reliable estimate of the causal effect of social-deservingness on welfare support. The following subsections cover (1) the simultaneous generation and measurement of the potential outcomes across a treatment and control condition; (2) an assessment of (im)balance between the measured characteristics of the synthetic respondents across the group conditions, revealing perfect balance; (3) a statistical test of the simultaneity assumption to ascertain whether time could confound results; and (4) a formalization of the statistical model, which in line with Bayesian inference will be used to estimate the causal effect of social-deservingness on welfare support.

4.3.1 Parallel Worlds

Generating potential outcomes is similar to the procedure used for generating life-histories. This will involve prompting the NLP-model to assume the character of the synthetic respondent by relying on the characteristics described in the previously generated life-histories. As mentioned, the Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) gets its name from Randomized Controlled Trials (RCTs, Coover and Angell 1907; Peirce and Jastrow 1885; Woodworth and Thorndike 1901), since its borrows heavily on its methodology and can be considered its synthetic counterpart. Just like an RCT, the SCT will involve assigning the synthetic respondents to group conditions with varying manipulations, followed by measuring the outcome. However, an SCT does not rely on randomized manipulation assignment, since every respondent can be assigned to every manipulation condition and have all their counterfactual outcomes measured. This involves simultaneously assigning each synthetic respondent to each group condition, ensuring that for each group assignment, no information about other group conditions are present, eliminating pre- or posttreatment bias that would otherwise need to have been accounted for. To avoid time being a possible confounder, it is important that this process, at least with respect to each synthetic respondent, occurs simultaneously across group conditions, which is termed the simultaneity assumption. Compliance with this assumption is implemented with the novel concept of parallel worlds-estimation, which exploits parallel computation (Gottlieb and Almasi 1989; Ozdoganlar and Endres 2021[1999]) to simultaneously generate and measure the counterfactual outcomes of each respondent by handling these processes in separate computational cores. If the simultaneity assumption is not violated, this will remove time as a confounder, though parallel worlds-estimation requires implementation on a machine that has as many computational cores as there are manipulation conditions.

With the above considerations in mind, the current demonstration involves replicating the results by Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023). As mentioned, these have established the causal effect of social deservingness on welfare support, which this demonstration is interested in replicating. For ease of overview, this relationship is provided graphically in figure 4.1. To test this relationship, the studies use vignettes to manipulate the level of social deservingness of a fictitious welfare recipient shown to the respondents. In this demonstration, two of their three manipulation conditions are replicated, which involve the vignettes describing a Lazy Welfare Recipient and an Unlucky Welfare Recipient, which they task the respondent with imagining before responding To what extent do you disagree or agree that the eligibility requirements for social welfare should be tightened for persons like him? (Aare and Petersen 2014). For simplicity, the former manipulation condition will be referred to as the control condition, while the latter will be the treatment condition. These vignettes can be reformulated as prompts (e.g., Ornstein et al. 2024), which are provided in table 4.4. The prompt adds realism-promoting context for the synthetic respondent, such as the notion that the respondent has chosen to participate in a survey and has already filled out questions regarding their background characteristics. This includes some standard survey introductory text that informs the respondent that the researchers are impartial and professional and care for the respondents honest answers. This flavor text serves to reduce the impact of social desirability (Edwards 1953; Krumpal 2013) and other demand characteristics (Masling 1966; Nichols and Maner 2008), such as expectancy effects (McDermott 1895: 34) and experimenter demand bias (Druckman 2015: 57-58), on respondent answers. The prompts include the response scale, since it is important to provide the NLP-model with the intended response format. In line with the replication, a 5-point Likert (1932) scale is used, however, other types of scales may be of greater use to capture other phenomena. Lastly, the prompt explicitly states that the respondent takes their time to imagine the welfare recipient, which serves to ensure that the response reflects a contemplated opinion. However, as empirical researchers are aware, not all human respondents take their time to read and comply with vignettes (Kane et al. 2023), and given how agreeable the GPT models generally are, it is likely that the responses will fail to reflect non-compliant and inattentive human respondents.

With one vignette being used in each manipulation condition, the synthetic respondents can then be simultaneously assigned to both conditions to provide their counterfactual responses. Similar to generating the life-histories, this again involves a for-loop iterating over each synthetic respondent, thus abiding by the iid and SUTVA assumptions. Unlike before, however, the loop implements a nested for-loop that implements the parallel worlds-estimation using parallel processing (Microsoft and Weston 2022b). This is applied when assigning a synthetic respondent to the manipulation conditions, where in each core, a call to OpenAIs API (2024a) of the gpt-4o-mini model is made, producing two independent API calls. As mentioned, this serves to reduce any time difference between observing each outcome across the manipulation conditions. Outside this parallel process, API calls are made continuously with a 3.1 second pause between each synthetic respondent, and a 10-second pause in case of an error. It should be further noted that a random Bernoulli-process determines which manipulation condition is first initialized in the parallel process, which serves to ensure that any idiosyncratic waits attributable to the initiating value are unbiased.

The below for-loop generates both counterfactual outcomes for each respondent, one for the Lazy Welfare Recipient and one for the Unlucky Welfare Recipient. The implementation of the parallel worlds-estimation procedure uses two independent cores, with one core being used to process each manipulation condition.

4.3.2 Group Balance

This paper has so far argued that implementing the Synthetic Causal Framework as a Synthetically Controlled Trial ensures perfect balance in the respondent characteristics across manipulation conditions. To empirically prove this (Stuart 2010), this subsection assesses the balance. This is done across all simulated characteristics, comparing their averages or frequencies across the control (Lazy Recipient) and the treatment (Unlucky Recipient) group conditions. Estimates of group differences are provided, including the log-odds of being assigned the treatment (Unlucky Recipient) group condition conditional on the characteristics, computed using a Frequentist logistic Bernoulli model (Berkson 1944; Cox 1958; Pearl and Reed 1920; Verhulst 1838) that uses mixed effects to account for each synthetic respondent being observed in both manipulation conditions. The theoretical expectation is that since each individual is assigned to each manipulation condition, there will be a perfect balance between groups and the log-odds of treatment will be 0, meaning that the probability of being assigned to either the control (Lazy Recipient) or treatment (Unlucky Recipient) group condition is 50/50. The results are provided in table 4.6.

The balance table reveals that there are no differences in any of the synthetic respondent characteristics across the manipulation conditions, meaning that results cannot be confounded by these characteristics (Stuart 2010). That there is perfect balance is further validated by taking the sum of differences and testing whether it is equal to 0, which is indeed found to be true. Similarly, the log-odds of receiving treatment conditional on the characteristics is 0, with effectively no estimation uncertanty. Accordingly, there is perfect sample balance on the measured characteristics, and given that there are no statistically significant differences (Mutz and Pemantle 2012: 3), this procedure for generating perfect balance can be expected to produce similarly perfect balances in other samples as well.

While the balance table only demonstrates perfect balance on the measured characteristics, given that every synthetic respondent is assigned to both manipulation conditions, thus providing every respondent with a perfect unit for comparison across conditions, it is here argued that there is perfect balance not only on the measured characteristics but also every unmeasured characteristic as well. This demonstrates the high internal validity of the SCF, especially when compared to other methods (e.g., the RCT) that only guarantees perfect balance on average, or asymptotically as a function of the sample size.

4.3.3 Testing Simultaneity

With group balance having been demonstrated to be perfect, a more relevant concern for researchers using the SCT is testing the simultaneity assumption. As mentioned, this assumption serves to avoid time confounding results, which would be possible if the generation and measurement of outcomes across manipulation conditions for the same individual varied. This was why the parallel worlds-estimation procedure was used when generating the outcome data, since parallel processing helped ensure that the generation occurred simultaneously in independent computational cores. However, this argument and procedure does not equate with the simultaneity assumption necessarily being valid, and it can be considered a reliable scientific practice to test assumptions when possible to see whether they hold (Hartman and Hidalgo 2018). The simultaneity assumption can be tested, since when generating the outcome, the time of receiving GPTs response was saved and stored in the data. This allows assessing whether the time difference between generating the outcomes across manipulation conditions is zero and whether the generation is biased towards favoring any manipulation condition. If the difference is zero, this means that the individual treatment effect (ITE) is unconfounded by time, however, should this not be true, another option is that the difference across all individuals is expectedly 0, which means that the average treatment effect (ATE) is unconfounded by time. Both conditions can be interesting to examine, though if the former holds, the second condition would necessarily be hold as well.

Testing that the difference in outcome generation across manipulation conditions is zero can be done following Hartman and Hidalgo (2018). They argue that contrary to common practice in null hypothesis significance testing (NHST), assumption tests need to a priori expect some violation of the assumptions (e.g., design flaws). This would be the null hypothesis (\(H_0\)) that the time difference (\(\delta\)) in the measurement time across group conditions is non-zero (\(H_0: \delta \neq 0\)), with the alternative hypothesis (\(H_a\)) being that it is zero (\(H_a: \delta = 0\)). This shifts the burden of proof to the researcher and creates a more conservative test, since the data will have to demonstrate that the results do not violate the simultaneity assumption. Unlike common approaches, the researcher is thus incentivised to collect more data (and thus gain more statistical power) to better prove their assumption true. As this study will primarily draw on Bayes theorem (Bayes and Price 1763; Laplace 2009[1814]) for statistical inference (Gelman et al. 2014, 2021; McElreath 2019), a Bayesian model is specified in table 4.7, though non-Bayesians can easily omit the specified priors to convert the model into its Frequentist counterpart.

Table 4.7: Simultaneity Test Model
\(|D|_{sd, i} \: \overset{\mathrm{iid}}{\sim} \: \mathcal{N}^+(\delta, \varsigma)\) 1.1
\(\delta \: \sim \: \mathcal{T}_3^+(.25, \: .25)\) 1.2
\(\varsigma \: \sim \: \mathcal{T}_3^+(1, \: .295)\) 1.3

NOTE: Bayesian Generalized (Gaussian) Linear Model. 1.1 is the likelihood-function, which specifies that the observations of the outcome variable \(|D|_{sd}\) (i.e., the absolute time difference between measurements across group conditions in time second standard deviations) are assumed to be identically and independently (i.e., iid) distributed as a half-normal (Gaussian) distribution, with the mean (\(\delta\)) and standard deviation (\(\varsigma\)) parameter being the desired estimands. 1.2 is the mean (\(\delta\)) prior, which is specified to be a half-Student t distributed, with a degrees of freedom (df) parameter of 3, mean of .25, and a standard deviation of .25. 1.3 is the prior for the (residual) standard deviation (\(\varsigma\)), specified as a half-Student t distribution, with a df of 3, mean of 1, and standard deviation of .295

In the model, the absolute time difference in time second standard deviations is treated as a non-negative continuous outcome that is assumed to be independently and identically distributed (iid), following a half-normal (Gaussian) distribution, meaning that the likelihood assumes no negative differences, which is appropriate given that the absolute time difference is being used. The quantities of interest (i.e., the estimands) are the mean and standard deviation of this time difference distribution. The specified priors provide a priori expectations for the intercept and standard deviation. Consistent with Hartman and Hidalgo (2018), the mean is specified to assume some difference, which is easily specified since the absolute time difference has been divided into standard deviation differences, allowing a medium time difference to be specified as a .25 standardized time difference (Funder and Ozer 2019), while its standard deviation is also specified as .25, which serves to make the priors be weakly informative, that is, to provide reasonable bounds but otherwise let the data speak for itself (Gelman et al. 2014: 55-56; McElreath 2019: 131). The prior is specified to follow a robust (OHagan 1979) Student t distribution Helmert (1875), which following Aki Vehtari, is specified with 3 degrees of freedom (df) to enable a finite mean and variance of the distribution. The (residual) standard deviation prior is similarly specified as a half-Student t with a df of 3. Its mean is specified as a 1 standard deviation of the time difference (i.e., .52 seconds), with a standard deviation of .295, which effectively means that the model is a priori expected to account for little to no variation in time difference, with the standard deviation being wide enough to let data to prove it wrong. This can be considered more conservative than other approaches (e.g., McElreath 2019), which typically specify the resdidual standard deviation prior so that the model is a priori expected to explain all or most variation in the outcome, which is arguably unreasonable for most models, at least in the social sciences.

The model is then fit to the data using brms (Brkner 2017, 2018), which implements the computationally efficient No-U-Turn algorithm (NUTS, Hoffman and Gelman 2014) for the Hamiltonian Markov-Chain Monte Carlo procedure (Duane et al. 1987; Neal 1993, 2011) to draw samples from the time difference posterior distribution. For computational efficiency and to assess whether the posterior has been reliably identified, 7 independent sampling chains are used. To increase the reliability of the drawn samples, each chain will first draw 2,000 samples for warmup. Following this, 40,000 samples will then be drawn in total, which serves to reliably identify the posterior by invoking the law of large numbers (Sen and Singer 1993). Inspecting the output using the Gelman-Rubin Convergence metric (\(\hat{R}\), Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021), the sampling chains are found to reliably converge to the same posterior distribution (\(\hat{R}\) < 1.01), with an approximately zero sampling error as indicated by the Monte-Carlo Standard Error (MCSE, Kruschke 2014), and a sufficiently large effective sample size (ESS 1,000, Brkner 2017) when accounting for autocorrelation between chains. The priors are validated to be uninformative relative to the data (Makowski et al. 2019a), meaning that they are unlikely to substantially impact the results. The posterior distribution for the absolute mean time difference (\(\hat{\delta}\)) parameter is displayed in figure 4.2, while summary statistics are provided in table 4.8.

Figure 4.2: Time Difference Between Measured Group Conditions

The results reveal that the a priori expectation of a some time difference in generating and measuring the counterfactual outcomes across the control (Lazy Recipient) and treatment (Unlucky Recipient) groups has been updated by the data resulting in a estimated average absolute time difference in time second standard deviations of .285 (SD = .087; 95% HDI[.118; .460]), which can be most credibly (40.58%) interpreted as a medium sized difference (Funder and Ozer 2019). In an unstandardized format, this can be more easily interpreted as an absolute difference of .15 seconds in the measurement time across groups.

As such, in this demonstration, there is some difference in the time of generating and measuring the counterfactual outcomes, which means that the estimated ITEs may be biased and confounded by time difference. However, it can be argued that the raw absolute time difference of merely .15 seconds is unlikely to cause substantial differences in the potential outcomes, which does lend some credence to the results, though this does not equate with the results being unbiased. With regards to the implementation of the parallel worlds-estimation procedure implemented here, the time difference is assessed to have a probability of 0% chance of happening if assuming the difference occurred by chance, making the difference statistically discernible from zero at conventional levels (\(p .05\)). This is corroborated by a posterior log-odds of 2.559 (SD = .525), which, following Raftery (1995), can be interpreted as positive evidence in favour of the hypothesis that this implementation of parallel worlds-estimation will generally fails to ensure that counterfactual outcomes are generated simultaneously. Accordingly, the simultaneity assumption can be proven as testable, and it would seem that further work is needed to create implementations that do not produce results that violate the simultaneity assumption and thus risk time confounding results.

4.4 Bayesian Inference

To replicate the analyses across Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023), the model used for statistical inference solely includes an intercept and coefficient for the difference between the control (Lazy Recipient) and treatment (Unlucky Recipient) manipulation conditions. Contrary to the original study, Bayesian inference is used, which can generally be considered superior in terms of interpretation and inference (Cohen 1994: 998-999; Pawitan 2001: 13; Clayton 2021; Gelman et al. 2021; Kruschke and Liddell 2018; McElreath 2019). A caveat of the SCT is that the data is to be transformed into a long format to take advantage of the two counterfactual outcome observations for each synthetic respondent. This, however, creates a respondent-clustered structure in the data, which would violate the iid assumption, because observations in this format would not be independent. This can be accounted for with a hierarchical/multilevel model (Gelman and Hill 2007; Yarkoni 2020) that specifies a fixed and respondent-varying intercepts. Also, just like Aare and Petersen (2014), the measured welfare support outcome is normalized, or min-maxed (i.e., rescaled 0-1), to ease interpretation and comparability. Using notation similar to Nalborczyk et al. (2019), the specified multilevel model is provided in table 4.9.

\(\beta_G \: \sim \: \mathcal{T}_3(0, \: .25)\) 1.3
\(\alpha_{i[id]} \: \sim \: \mathcal{T}_3(\alpha, \: \sigma_{id})\) 1.4
\(\alpha \: \sim \: \mathcal{T}_3(.362, \: .434)\) 1.5

NOTE: Multilevel Bayesian Generalized (Gaussian) Linear Model with respondent ID-varying intercepts. 1.1 is the likelihood-function, which specifies that the observations of the outcome variable \(Y\) (i.e., welfare support) are assumed to be identically and independently (i.e., iid) distributed as a normal (Gaussian) distribution, with the mean and standard deviation parameter being the desired estimands. 1.2 is the affine function (Boyd and Vandenberghe 2018) of the mean parameter, which consists of a fixed (i.e., US-level) intercept, a fixed coefficient indicating the effect of group assignment (i.e., the social deservingness of the vignette welfare recipient), and random (i.e., respondent-level) varying intercepts. 1.3 is the prior of the group assignment coefficient, specified as a Student t distribution, with a 3 degrees of freedom (df) parameter, a mean of 0, and standard deviation of .25. 1.4 is the prior for the respondent-level varying intercepts, Student t distributed, with a df of 3, the mean being the US-level intercept, and an unknown standard deviation parameter. 1.5 is the intercept prior or the hyper prior for the mean parameter of the respondent-varying intercepts, being Student t distributed, df of 3, mean of .362, and a standard deviation of .434. 1.6 is the hyper prior for the standard deviation parameter of the respondent-varying intercepts, being distributed as a half-Student t, with a df of 3, mean of 0, and standard deviation of .25. 1.7 is the prior for the residual standard deviation of the outcome (RMSE), specified as a half-Student t distribution, with a df of 3, mean of .434, and standard deviation of .132.

The model assumes that the outcome distribution (i.e., welfare support) is identically and independently (iid), normal (Gaussian) distributed, with its mean and standard deviation being the estimands. The mean is modeled as an affine function (Boyd and Vandenberghe 2018), consisting of a fixed (global) intercept, a coefficient indicating the effect of seeing an Unlucky compared to a Lazy welfare recipient, and respondent-varying intercepts. Since the purpose is to compare the results to Aare and Petersen (2014) to validate the SCFs generalizability, the priors do not incorporate information from Aare and Petersen (2014) but instead are specified as weakly informative, with mean and standard deviation parameters similar to those specified when testing the simultaneity assumption (table 4.7), though this model includes a hyper prior for the respondent-varying intercepts, as well as priors for its mean and standard deviation parameter that a priori expect little to no respondent-variability.

With this model specified, data is then formatted in a way to ease interpretation of the output. This means that the manipulations conditions are recoded so that the coefficient will indicate the effect of an increasing level of social deservingness on the welfare support of the synthetic respondent. As such, it is a priori expected that increasing social deservingness increases welfare support, which will be supported by the coefficient being (1) non-negative, as indicated by a probability of direction (\(p_d\), Makowski et al. 2019b) equal to or greater than 95% (i.e., \(p_d .95\)); (2) statistically discernible from zero, given by a p-value (Arbuthnot 1710; Pearson 1900) equal to or less than an \(\alpha\) of .05 (i.e., \(p .05\), Fisher 1970); and (3) that the relative evidence in the form of the posterior log-odds (a Bayes factor variant, Kass and Raftery 1995) indicates that the (alternative) hypothesis of a relationship between social deservingness and welfare is more probable than the (null) hypothesis of no such relationship (i.e., \(BF_{ln} > 0\)). Note that the original sample size of 100 in this long-format data provides an effective sample size of 200, since each synthetic respondent is observed two times, one for each counterfactual outcome. With these considerations in mind, an analysis of the results can be conducted.

5 Analyses

5.1 Confirmatory Analysis

To examine the theorized relationship between social deservingness and welfare support, the specified statistical model (see table 4.9) is fitted to the data. Similar to testing the simultaneity assumption, this procedures uses NUTS Hamiltonian MCMC (Hoffman and Gelman 2014) implemented in brms (Brkner 2017, 2018), using 7 independent sampling chains, with 2,000 warmup samples per chain, followed by a total of 40,000 post-warmup samples. Results are provided graphically and metrically, with the estimated welfare support across groups being illustrated in figure 5.1, the size of the group difference in figure 5.2, and summary statistics in table 5.1. Inspecting these reveal that chain convergence was excellent (\(\hat{R}\) < 1.01, Gelman and Rubin 1992; Vehtari et al. 2021), with a sufficient effective sample size (ESS > 1,000, Brkner 2017), almost no sampling uncertainty (MCSE < .000, Kruschke 2014), and priors were validated as uninformative relative to the data (Makowski et al. 2019a). However, the posterior predictive p-value (\(PP_P\), Gelman et al. 1996) of 0.999 indicates a relatively low model fit, as the model tends to make exaggerated estimates of welfare support, possibly due to the low sample size. This is somewhat countered, though, by the Bayesian loo-adjusted \(R^2\) (Gelman et al. 2019) of .696 (SD = .034; 95% HDI[.627; .759]), indicating that the models estimated out-of-sample predictive power can be interpreted as substantial (Cohen 1988), revealing a relatively high fit. As such, focus can now be directed to the parameters of the model.

This is consistent with the theorized relationship and is further corroborated by a posterior log-odds of 59.929 (SD = .013), which, following Raftery (1995), can be interpreted as very strong evidence in favour of the relationship between social deservingness and welfare support.

Do the results replicate the meta-analysis? Arguably, yes and no. The positive estimated effect of social deservingness on welfare support, as well as the relative evidence that favors the hypothesized relationship, does replicate the overall result and conclusion by Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023), thus strengthening the scientific evidence for a relationship between social deservingness and welfare support. However, the difference in estimated effect in this study of .719 (SD = .033; 95% HDI[.653; .784]) and the meta-analytic estimate of .32 (SD = .07; 95% HDI[.16; .48]) can be considered quite substantial. This relevant discrepancy could be attributable to relying on synthetic respondents, but it could also be attributable to a type M error (Gelman and Carlin 2014) and differences in sample compositions, such as the overrepresentation of republicans/conservatives in this study, where social deservingness would expectedly have a larger effect. This can be sought accounted for by analyzing the heterogeneity of the estimated effect across preferred political party and political ideology.

5.2 Heterogeneity Analysis

A heterogeneity analysis can be conducted to test the aforementioned expectation that the effect of social deservingness on welfare support interacts with preferred political party and political ideology. If this is the case, the sample-population imbalance on these characteristics could explain the discrepancy between the results in the main analysis and the meta-analysis results by Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023). This is first tested by specifying a Frequentist model equivalent to the one in the main analysis, that besides dropping the prior specifications, includes an interaction term between the manipulation condition and preferred political party. The second model is the same, except for the interaction term involving political ideology instead. Fitting the models to data, results reveal that the interaction term in both models are statistically discernible from zero (\(p .05\)). Since the same conclusion is derived from both models, to remain concise, only the results from the political party interaction-model is shown here, provided metrically in the table below.

As is evident by these results, the effect of social deservingness on welfare support among respondents that prefer the Democratic Party, the estimate effect is .34 (SE = .02; 95% CI[.31; .37]), while the effect for republicans is substantially higher. The effect among democrats is substantially closer to the meta-analytic estimate of .32 (SD = .07; 95% HDI[.16; .48]) from Aare and Petersen (2014), Mummolo and Peterson (2019), and Kane et al. (2023), and if this study has a slight overrepresentation of democrats similar to the population, the ATE estimated in the main analysis, would have been much more similar to the meta-analytic estimate. As such, the discrepancy is consistent with differences in sample composition, specifically the overrepresentation of republicans/conservatives, for whom the effect of social deservingness on welfare support if larger than democrats/liberals. This means that, when accounting for this sample-population imbalance, that this application of the Synthetic Causal Framework can be considered to have successfully replicated the relationship between social deservingness and welfare support. This indicates that the SCF can be considered not only a reliable approach to causal inference that guarantees a high internal validity, but a framework that produces results that can generalize to human populations. To wrap up these results, a cost analysis will summarize the resources used in this demonstration of the Synthetic Causal Framework.

5.3 Cost Analysis

The costs associated with generating the life-histories and the preceding analyses can be estimated using the token costs. Costs vary for input and output tokens, as well as across OpenAIs (2024a) models, with the selected gpt-4o-mini being the cheapest at the time of writing, charging on average 0.375 $US per 1,000,000 input/output tokens used.

Financial Costs. In terms of financial costs, generating 100 life-histories and two counterfactual outcomes with the provided prompts and specified settings, the total cost is estimated to be .05 $US. This means that the expected financial cost per respondent is .00 (SD = .00) $US. Compared to studies that rely on human participants, this can be considered relatively cheap, especially considering the substantial gain in internal validity to relying on this procedure to generate synthetic respondents.

Time Costs. Another relevant cost for researchers to consider is time costs. Besides setting up the relatively easily adaptable code used in this study for implementing the synthetically controlled trial, as well as fitting the Bayesian models to the data, generating the life-histories and the outcomes for the Lazy and Unlucky welfare recipients took a total of 23.55 minutes. With 100 synthetic respondents, the expected time cost per respondent is 14.13 (SD = .00) seconds. Compared to human studies that may take weeks if not months to obtain a sizable sample, this can be considered a substantial reduction in the time taking to obtain survey responses. This means that researchers can save time by conducting a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) compared to having to rely on human respondents.

This cost analysis thus reveals that the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF), through is implementation as an SCT, can be considered less costly, both in terms of the financial and time resources needed to conduct a study. The SCT can thus save resources for researchers, and the bar needed to conduct a study with a high internal validity is substantially lowered, thus increasing the availability for researchers to make causal inferences across disciplines.

6 Discussion

Given the results produced by the implementation of a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) in this study, a series of methodological concerns can be discussed. This includes possible implications for the internal validity, external validity, ecological validity, implementation, and costs of this current rendition of the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF).

Internal Validity. The Synthetic Causal Framework serves to provide researchers with an alternative for drawing reliable causal inference. As formalized and demonstrated, the framework provides a sound theoretical approach for ensuring that estimates are solely attributable to researcher manipulation of the theorized cause. Since each individual is assigned all manipulation conditions, there is no confounding of results due to perfect balance between conditions. The SCF addresses time as a relevant confounder and posits parallel worlds-estimation as an approach to avoid this, though the current parallel processing implementation did not produce the necessary simultaneous generation and measurement of all counterfactual outcomes, allowing the ITEs and ATE to be confounded by time. This is possibly attributable to the systematic differences in prompt length, since the Unlucky Welfare Recipient vignette was slightly longer than the Lazy Welfare Recipient vignette, which could impact the time needed for the NLP-model to process the input. Nonetheless, by introducing the simultaneity assumption, and tests for this assumption, the SCF introduces new considerations of potential confounders, thus setting a higher bar for what reliable causal inference entails.

External Validity. In terms of external validity, the Synthetic Causal Framework arguably makes a trade-off between internal and external validity by relying on synthetic respondents rather than human respondents. This is a trade-off common to experimental designs, and while this may be a concern for some researchers, others have found no discernible impact on the external validity of results (Druckman 2015: 62). Some even argue for superior external validity of results (Samii 2016), at least compared to non-experimental designs, since efforts to isolate causal effects can introduce new biases (Wan et al. 2024) and reduce transparency in what population to infer results to (Aronow and Samii 2016). Nevertheless, the implemented SCT aims for an external validity similar to survey experiments by simulating human characteristics and generating life-histories to promote a more realistic NLP-driven behavior. This was corroborated by the ability to closely replicate the established relationship between social deservingness and welfare support. Despite this, it remains unlikely that synthetic respondents fully capture the nuanced (and sometimes idiosyncratic) behavior of human individuals. Similarly, it will take more studies to establish whether the SCF and its implementations can consistently produce results that generalize to human populations. Until then, generalizing synthetic results to human population should be considered with caution.

Ecological Validity. Similar to external validity, the ecological validity of Synthetic Causal Framework-based results heavily depend on the ability of the used NLP-models to realistically mimic human behavior. To ensure a high ecological validity, it is likely that more characteristics will need to be simulated to provide the NLP-model with the necessary context to properly infer the behavior of such a person in real life. Such characteristics could potentially include, for example, personality traits and other psychological characteristics that have a great bearing on human everyday behavior. It is also likely that the characteristics that are relevant to simulate will vary depending on the research question. For example, religious affiliation could be a relevant characteristic to simulate if investigating causes that impact whether individuals favor Israel or Palestine in the currently ongoing conflict. It is likely that the ecological validity varies between NLP-models, and given their constant improvement, future models could likely outperform the gpt-4o-mini model used here.

Implementations & Costs. The implementation of the Synthetic Causal Framework as a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) served as an analogue to the popular Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT, Coover and Angell 1907; Peirce and Jastrow 1885; Woodworth and Thorndike 1901), which demonstrated how the framework could be implemented to draw reliable causal inference. This procedure could be considered relatively cheap in terms of both financial and time costs, making it an easily implementable and cheap alternative for researchers interested in causal inference. It should be noted that the SCF is not restricted to SCTs but could potentially be implemented in alternative ways depending on the research question and the phenomenon being studied. An implementation of the SCF need not mimic a survey setting, and synthetic human behavior could be studied in multiple ways. An example that draws on another causal methodology include the Regression Discontinuity Design (RDD, Skovron and Titiunik 2015; Thistlethwaite and Campbell 1960), popular in policy analyses, where synthetic respondents could be observed for a time period until they are exposed to some treatment that is theorized to impact an outcome of interest. Alternative implementations may affect financial costs, such as if more or lengthier prompts are needed, and the time costs will likely increase if more requests from the NLP-model are made. The adaptability of the SCF and the ongoing development of NLP-models, however, does provide researchers with the ability to develop their own implementations of the SCF that may become cheaper and more reliable over time.

Having discussed these concerns, the Synthetic Causal Framework provides researchers with a needed alternative to ensure the high internal validity necessary to draw reliable causal inference when a phenomenon of interest cannot be manipulated. These results could then be generalized to human populations, though some caution is warranted given the novelty of the framework. The SCF can be easily implemented, for example, as a Synthetically Controlled Trial, and is cheap in terms of financial and time costs. While concerns for the generalizability of SCF-based results to human populations remain warranted, advances in the implementation of the SCF and the ability of NLP-models to realistically mimic human individuals will likely increase over time.

7 Conclusion

This paper has introduced the Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF), a novel framework for drawing causal inference by generating respondents using an NLP-based synthesis of simulated and real human data. The primary purpose of the SCF is to solve the inability of researchers to reliably draw causal inference when the theorized cause cannot be manipulated, either by the researchers themselves, as in Randomized Controlled Trials (RCTs, Coover and Angell 1907; Peirce and Jastrow 1885; Woodworth and Thorndike 1901), or through natural processes, such as in natural experiments (Dunning 2008). The SCF solves this issue by simulating data and synthesizing it with real human data using Natural Language Processing (NLP) models, trained to mimic human behavior as expressed through language. In this NLP-based environment, researchers can vary manipulations and simultaneously observe all counterfactual outcomes resulting from these manipulations. With every respondent being in all manipulation conditions, the SCF ensures a perfect balance between the treatment and control groups, thus guaranteeing no confounding of results.

The SCF was formalized using the Neyman-Rubin Potential Outcomes Framework (Imbens and Rubin 2015), providing analytical expressions of its underlying logic and assumptions. A demonstration followed in the form of a Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) that sought to replicate the established relationship between social deservingness and welfare support. This demonstration showed how to simulate respondent characteristics proportional to the population of the United States, making results more representative of that population. It was then shown how to create prompts to generate life-histories for the simulated respondent, adding extra nuance to the simulated characteristics, which served to make the selected NLP-model, OpenAIs (2024a) gpt-4o-mini, more capable of realistically imitating the behavior of a person with those traits. An implementation of parallel worlds-estimation was provided, which utilized parallel processing to generate and measure two counterfactual levels of welfare support from exposure to a Lazy and Unlucky welfare recipient vignette. The replication then proved perfect group balance in terms of the simulated characteristics and tested the simultaneity assumption, finding a modest time difference between groups, making results confoundable by time differences. A Bayesian mixed-effects statistical model was specified, producing results that following an adjustment for population-sample imbalance, closely replicated the human-based results of an effect of social deservingness on welfare support. As such, the SCF offers a novel alternative for researchers to reliably draw causal inference, with a currently promising generalizability to human populations. Future developments of the SCF are expected in future studies, which will expectedly further increase its scientific utility.

10.2 Software Specifications

This document was created on a Windows 10 x64 (build 19045) operating system (OS) on the 2024-10-16 15:16 CEST (Timezone: Europe/Copenhagen). The machine has 8 cores available, and the range of doubles is \(2.23e^{-308}\) - \(1.8e^{+308}\).

All code is written in R version 4.4.1 (2024-06-14 ucrt), while the document is written with markdown (Gruber 2014) and LaTeX (Lamport 1986) in the RStudio version 2024.4.2.764, using the R packages knitr (Xie 2024b; v1.47, Xie 2014, 2015), markdown (v1.13, Xie et al. 2024), rmarkdown (Allaire et al. 2024; v2.27, Xie et al. 2018, 2020), and bookdown (Xie 2024a; v0.40, Xie 2016) . The code makes extensive use of R packages that are part of the tidyverse (v2.0.0, Wickham et al. 2019), including readr (v2.1.5, Wickham et al. 2024), stringr (v1.5.1, Wickham 2023), tidytext (v0.4.2, Silge and Robinson 2016). All graphs were produced with ggplot2 (v3.5.1, Wickham 2016), bayesplot (v1.11.1, Gabry et al. 2019), tidybayes (v3.0.6, Kay 2023), dagitty (v0.3.4, Textor et al. 2016), ggdag (v0.2.13, Barrett 2024), latex2exp (v0.9.6, Meschiari 2022), and ggpubr (v0.6.0, Kassambara 2023). Calls to OpenAIs API was done with the openai R package (v0.4.1, Rudnytskyi 2023), while the implementation of parallel processing necessary for the parallel worlds-estimation procedure was achieved using the parallel (v4.4.1, R Core Team 2024), doParallel (v1.0.17, Microsoft and Weston 2022a), and foreach (v1.5.2, Microsoft and Weston 2022b) R packages. The seed for random number generation (RNG) was determined using the random (v0.2.6, Eddelbuettel 2017) R package, which relies on algorithms by random.org. Statistical inference was conducted using the R packages lme4 (v1.1.35.4, Bates et al. 2015), randomForest (v4.7.1.1, Liaw and Wiener 2002), mgcv (v1.9.1, Wood 2004, 2011, 2017), brms (v2.21.0, Brkner 2017, 2018), bayestestR (v0.13.2, Makowski et al. 2019a), effectsize (v0.8.9, Ben-Shachar et al. 2020), rQCC (Park et al. 2022; v2.22.12, Park and Wang 2020, 2022), and HuraultMisc (v1.1.1, Hurault 2021). Data was estimated and formatted using the scrutiny (v0.4.0, Jung 2024), weights (v1.0.4, Pasek et al. 2021), scales (v1.3.0, Wickham et al. 2023), lsa (v0.73.3, Wild 2022), kableExtra (v1.4.0, Zhu 2024), and summarytools (v1.0.1, Comtois 2022) R packages.

The Synthetic Causal Framework (SCF) and its implementation as the Synthetically Controlled Trial (SCT) are original concepts by Emil Meyer-Hansen, conceived as part of the authors PhD project proposal for Aarhus University (submitted 2024-9-5, will be made freely available at a later date). In their current states, Emil Meyer-Hansen is the sole author and contributor to their ongoing development, conceptualization, formalization, and implementation. To follow the ongoing development, visit: (https://github.com/emeyer-hansen/synthetic_causal_framework). For correspondence, contact the author via email: emil098meyerhansen@gmail.com.

Please, if you use, refer to, and/or continue the development of the SCF and/or SCT, provide proper reference and citation to their original author. An example of proper citation is provided below:

  • Meyer-Hansen, E. (2024): The Synthetic Causal Framework: An NLP-based Solution to the Fundamental Problem of Causal Inference, version 2024-10-16-15-18, Preview on GitHub: (https://github.com/emeyer-hansen/synthetic_causal_framework).

  2. Ethnoracial group is a term used to denote the overlapping racial/ethnic/national terminology employed in the US (e.g., White, African-American, Chinese, etc.)

  3. The level of shared information between the simulated sample and the population was estimated by a novel application of cosine similarity (Kozlowski et al. 2019: 910-911; Mikolov et al. 2013: 5). Analogous to computational text analysis (Theocharis and Jungherr 2021), this exploits that cosine similarity is derivable from Token Frequency Documents (TDF, e.g., Rheault and Cochrane 2020; Rodriguez et al. 2023a: 6; Rodriguez et al. 2023b: 5), which can be changed to an Information Frequency Matrix (IFM) that reflects the frequency of values (i.e., information) occurring in the sample and population. With cosine similarity being scaled 0-1 in such instances, cosine similarity here reflects the shared information between the sample and population.

  4. The r correlation coefficient is here (properly) accredited to both Francis Galton and Karl Pearson (see Stigler 1989)
